        <section xml:id="sec-changeinxy">
          <title>*Connecting <m>\Delta y</m> and <m>\Delta x</m></title>
          
          <aside>
            <p>
              This section is inspired by Thompson's <em>Calculus Made Easy</em>
            </p>
          </aside>
      
          <p>
            We can now introduce one of the central ideas in calculus, which we will come back in more detail in Part III of the class.  
            For now, our main goal is to better see the connection between change graphs (which have clear economic and business applications) and functions and their combinations (which does not).
          </p>
          <p>
            There are three key ideas.  
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The independent variable <m>x</m> and dependent variable <m>y</m> both change and grow.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The change in input <m>x</m> is written (denoted) <m>\Delta x</m>, and the change in output <m>y</m> is written <m>\Delta y</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Because <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are related by some function <m>y=f(x)</m>, then <m>\Delta y</m> and <m>\Delta x</m> are aso related. 
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            Our goal is to understand how to find <m>\Delta y</m> from <m>x</m> and <m>\Delta x</m> and, eventually, to understand the relationship between <m>\Delta y</m> and <m>\Delta x</m>.
          </p>
      
          <p>We can make these ideas precise in a definition</p>
          <definition xml:id="def-Deltayfromx1x2">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Given a function <m>y=f(x)</m> and two inputs <m>x_1,x_2</m>, and corresponding outputs <m>y_1 = f(x_1)</m> and <m>y_2=f(x_2)</m>, we say that the <em>change in <m>y</m> between <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m></em> is written <m>\Delta y</m>. 
                There are three different, but equivalent, ways that we will think about <m>\Delta y</m>
                <mdn>
                  <mrow> \Delta y \amp = y_2 - y_1 </mrow>
                  <mrow> \Delta y \amp = f(x_2) - f(x_1)</mrow>
                  <mrow> \Delta y \amp = f(x_1 + \Delta x) - f(x_1)</mrow>
                </mdn>
                These first two are saying the same thing because we always write <m>y_1 = f(x_1)</m> and <m>y_2=f(x_2)</m>.
                We need the third equation when we only know only <m>x_1</m> and <m>\Delta x = x_2-x_1</m>, but not <m>x_2</m>.  In that case, we solve for <m>x_2 = x_1 + \Delta x</m>, and compute <m>y_2 = f(x_2) = f(x_1+\Delta x)</m>.
              </p>
              
            </statement>
          </definition>
          <exploration xml:id="ex_deltay_variable">
            <introduction>
              <p>
                Suppose that <m>y = f(x) = x^2</m>, that <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> are two unknown inputs, and that <m>\Delta x = x_2-x_1</m> is the change in input.
              </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p> 
                  Find the value <m>y_1</m> of the function at input <m>x_1</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  To find the value of <m>y=f(x)</m> at <m>x=x_1</m>, just plug this value into our function <m>f(x)=x^2</m>
                  <me>y_1 = f(x_1) = \Big(x_1\Big)^2</me>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Find the value <m>y_2</m> of the function at input <m>x_2</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  As before, we could just plug <m>x=x_2</m> into our function <m>f(x) = x^2</m> to get
                  <me>y_2 = f(x_2) = \Big(x_2\Big)^2</me>
                  But we can get a more informative answer by using the fact that because <m>\Delta x = x_2 - x_1</m>, then <m>x_2 = x_1 + \Delta x</m>.  Plugging this into our equation gives
                  <md>
                    <mrow> y_2 \amp = f(x_1 + \Delta x)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big)\cdot \Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big)</mrow>
                    <mrow> y_2 \amp = (x_1)^2 + 2(x_1)(\Delta x) + (\Delta x)^2</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Find <m>\Delta y</m> in terms of <m>\Delta x</m> and <m>x_1</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Recall that <m>\Delta y</m> is just the change in <m>y</m> that occurs as a result of changing the input from <m>x_1</m> to <m>x_2</m>.  Mathematically, this gives us 
                  <md>
                    <mrow> \Delta y \amp = \Big(y_2\Big) - \Big(y_1\Big)</mrow>
                  </md>
                  Using our work above, we know <m>y_1 = (x_1)^2</m> and that <m>y_2 = (x_1)^2 + 2(x_1)(\Delta x) + (\Delta x)^2</m>.  This gives us 
                  <md>
                    <mrow> \Delta y \amp = \Big(y_2\Big) - \Big(y_1\Big)</mrow>
                    <mrow>          \amp = \Big((x_1)^2 + 2(x_1)(\Delta x) + (\Delta x)^2\Big) - (x_1)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> \Delta y \amp = 2(x_1)(\Delta x)+(\Delta x)^2</mrow>
                  </md>
                  We now have a formula for how the change in output <m>\Delta y</m> depends on the change in input <m>\Delta x</m>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Find an equation for <m>\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m>.  
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We have already see that 
                  <md>
                    <mrow> \Delta y \amp = 2(x_1)(\Delta x)+(\Delta x)^2</mrow>
                  </md>
                  We can factor a term of <m>\Delta x</m> out of the right hand side. 
                  <md>
                    <mrow> \Delta y \amp = (\Delta x)\cdot \Big(2(x_1)+(\Delta x)\Big)</mrow>
                  </md>
                  Now, we can divide both sides by <m>\Delta x</m> to get a <m>\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m> on the left hand side.
                  <md>
                    <mrow> \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} \amp =  2(x_1)+(\Delta x)</mrow>
                  </md>
                  We will see what this term really means later in the course, when we discuss rates of change and slopes.  
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
          </exploration>
          <p>
            In the next chapter, we will see a special case of <m>\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m> when we review linear functions.  We will also introduce a number of functions that play an important role in economics and business. We close with a quick example using the total cost function <m>C(x)</m>
          </p>
          <exploration xml:id="ex_deltay_numerical">
            <introduction>
              <p>
                Suppose that <m>C(x)= 0.01 x^2 - x+ 50</m> gives the total cost of purchasing <m>x</m> barrels of oil. 
              </p>
              <p>
                In the past, you have purchased <m>x=300</m> barrels of oil each month. But now you are thinking of buying a bit more oil.  You want to know how much your costs will change as a result of this increase in purchase volume. 
              </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Find the cost of <m>300</m> barrels of oil.  
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>C(300) = 0.01(300)^2 - 300 + 50 = 650</m>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Find the change in cost <m>\Delta C</m> between <m>x_1=300</m> barrels and <m>x_2=400</m> barrels.
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  The formula for change in cost is <me>\Delta C = C_2 - C_1</me>
                  Here, the first cost is the cost of 300 barrels
                  <me>C_1 = C(300) = 0.01(300)^2 - 300 + 50 = 650</me>
                  The second cost is the cost of 600 barrels
                  <me>C_2 = C(400) = 0.01(400)^2 - 400 + 50 = 1250  </me>
                  The change in the cost is therefore 
                  <me>\Delta C = C(400) - C(300) = 1250 - 650 = 600</me>
                  The <m>\Delta x=100</m> additional barrels will increase the total cost by $600 (an average of $6 per barrel).
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Suppose you want to increase your purchase volume from <m>x_1=300</m> by <m>\Delta x = 10</m> barrels. What is the change in cost going to be?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We want to compare the cost of 
                  <me>
                    x_1=300
                  </me> 
                  and 
                  <me>
                    x_2 = 300+\Delta x = 300+10=310
                  </me> 
                  barrels of oil.  We can compute the costs separately, and then subtract them.
                  <md>
                    <mrow>C_1 \amp= C(300) = 650 </mrow>
                    <mrow>C_2 \amp= C(300+10) = C(310) = 0.01(310)^2 - 310 + 50 = 701 </mrow>
                  </md>
                  Subtracting these total costs gives us the change in cost 
                  <me> \Delta C = C_2 - C_1 = C(310)- C(300) =51</me>
                  The cost will increase <m>\Delta C = 51</m> dollars
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  You are not sure how much you want to increase the purchase by.  In other words, <m>x_1=300</m>, but <m>\Delta x</m> is unknown. 
                  Find an equation for the change in cost <m>\Delta C</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We want to find <me>\Delta C = C_2 - C_1 = C(x_2) - C(x_1)</me>.
                  We know that <m>x_1 = 300</m>, but we do not know <m>x_2</m>.  Therefore, we must write <me>x_2 = x_1 + \Delta x= 300 + \Delta x</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                  We can now compute <m>C_1</m> and <m>C_2</m>
                  <me>C_1 = C(300) = 0.01(300)^2 - 300 + 50 = 650</me>
                  and 
                  <md>
                    <mrow>C_2 \amp = C\Big(300 + \Delta x\Big)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 0.01\Big(300 + \Delta x\Big)^2 - \Big(300 + \Delta x\Big) + 50 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 0.01\Big(300\cdot 300 + 2\cdot 300\cdot \Delta x + (\Delta x)^2\Big) - \Big(300 + \Delta x\Big) + 50 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 900 + 6\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 - 300 - \Delta x + 50 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 650 + 5\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2  </mrow>
                  </md>
                  We have found that 
                  <md>
                    <mrow> C_1 \amp = 650 </mrow>
                    <mrow> C_2 \amp = 650 + 5\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2  </mrow>
                  </md>
                  We can now compute 
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\Delta C \amp = C_2 - C_1 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \Big(650+5\Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2\Big) - \Big(650\Big)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\Delta C \amp = 5\Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 </mrow>
                  </md>
                  
                </p>
      
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  You are not sure how much you want to increase the purchase by.  In other words, <m>x_1=300</m>, but <m>\Delta x</m> is unknown. 
                  Find an equation for <m>\dfrac{\Delta C}{\Delta x}</m>.          
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We found above that for <m>C(x) =  0.01 x^2 - x+ 50</m>,  <m>x_1=300</m>, and unknown (arbitarary) <m>\Delta x</m> that 
                    <me> \Delta C = 5\Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 </me>
                  To find <m>\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta x}</m>, we first need to factor <m>\Delta x</m> out of every term on the right side. 
                   <me> \Delta C = \Delta x(5 + 0.01 \Delta x) </me>
                  Now we can divide both sides by <m>\Delta x</m>
                  <me> \dfrac{\Delta C}{\Delta x} = 5 + 0.01 \Delta x </me>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  You want to look at how changing quantity impacts the change in cost in general.  In other words, find a formula for <m>\Delta C</m> and <m>\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta x}</m> terms of an <em>unknown</em> starting quantity <m>x_1</m> and <em>unknown</em> change <m>\Delta x</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We want to find <me>\Delta C = C_2 - C_1 = C(x_2) - C(x_1)</me>.
                  We do not know <m>x_1,x_2</m>, so we must write <me>x_2 = x_1 + \Delta x</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                  We can now compute <m>C_1</m> and <m>C_2</m>
                  <me>C_1 = C(x_1) = 0.01(x_1)^2 - x_1 + 50 </me>
                  and 
                  <md>
                    <mrow>C_2 \amp = C\Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 0.01\Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big)^2 - \Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big) + 50 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 0.01\Big(x_1\cdot x_1 + 2\cdot x_1\cdot \Delta x + (\Delta x)^2\Big) - \Big(x_1 + \Delta x\Big) + 50 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 0.01{x_1}^2 + 0.02x_1\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 - x_1 - \Delta x + 50 </mrow>
                  </md>
                  We have found that 
                  <md>
                    <mrow>C_1 \amp = 0.01(x_1)^2 - x_1 + 50</mrow>
                    <mrow>C_2 \amp = 0.01{x_1}^2 + 0.02x_1\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 - x_1 - \Delta x + 50</mrow>
                  </md>
                  We can now compute 
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\Delta C \amp = C_2 - C_1 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \Big(0.01{x_1}^2 + 0.02x_1\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 - x_1 - \Delta x + 50   \Big) - \Big(0.01(x_1)^2 - x_1 + 50\Big)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\Delta C \amp = 0.02x_1\cdot \Delta x + 0.01(\Delta x)^2 - \Delta x   </mrow>
                  </md>
                  To find <m>\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta x}</m>, we need to factor a <m>\Delta x</m> out of every term on the right, and then divide by it. 
                  <me>\Delta C  = (\Delta x) \Big( 0.02x_1 + 0.01 \Delta x - 1\Big)  </me>
                  <me> \dfrac{\Delta C}{\Delta x}  =  0.02x_1 + 0.01 \Delta x - 1 </me>
                </p>
      
              </solution>
            </task>
          </exploration>
        </section>
